"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-08-05-imane-khelif-sends-message-bullies-ahead-olympic-semi-final-21360673\", \"text\": \"Imane Khelif has hit out at the 'bullying' she has received during the Olympics, describing it as 'harmful to human dignity'.  Khelif'sparticipation at the Paris Olympics has come under scrutinyafter she and Lin Yu-ting - who areboth now guaranteed medals-were disqualified from last year's Word Championships.  At the time, the International Boxing Association (IBA) said both fighters failed gender eligibility tests, but theInternational Olympic Committeehas cast doubt over the validity of the tests.  TheIOC have also insisted both fighters were 'born women and raised women'but that has not stopped some fans from complaining about their presence in Paris.  In her first sit-down interview since the Olympics started, Khelif has criticised the treatment she has received and has asked fans to 'refrain from bullying'.  'I send a message to all the people of the world to uphold the Olympic principles and the Olympic Charter, to refrain from bullying all athletes, because this has effects, massive effects,' she told SNTV.  'It can destroy people, it can kill people's thoughts, spirit and mind. It can divide people. And because of that, I ask them to refrain from bullying.'  Khelif also said her family are 'worried' about her, though she does not want the ongoing controversy to harm her chances of winning Olympic gold in Paris.  'I am in contact with my family two days a week,' the 25-year-old said. 'I hope that they were not affected deeply.  'They are worried about me. God willing, this crisis will culminate in a gold medal, and that would be the best response.'  To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tbrowser thatsupports HTML5 \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tvideo  Up Next  Asked how aware she was of the debate over her participation at the Games, Khelif added: 'Honestly, I do not follow social media.  'There is a mental health team that does not let us follow social media, especially in the Olympic Games, whether me or other athletes. I am here to compete and get a good result.'  Khelif faces Thailand's Janjaem Suwannapheng on Tuesday in Paris. If victorious, she will fight for Olympic gold on Friday.  Looking ahead to the semi-final bout,Suwannapheng\\u00a0said she was not 'afraid' of Khelifand is determined to win gold.  'I have improved since then and I will fight with all I have got,' Suwannapheng told Thai newspaperKhaosod.  'I have looked into it too, about her hormones, and I know she's lost to female boxers before, but that was a long time ago.  'I am not sure if she's got stronger or if her male hormones have increased. But if we meet again, I am not afraid because we are evenly matched.  'I have prepared my body well too, trained a lot. I just think, no matter how strong or tough, we are both human, we both have two fists.  'Having come this far, I want to go all the way to the gold medal.'  Taiwanese boxerLin, meanwhile, takes on Turkey's Esra Yildiz Kahraman in Wednesday's semi-final in the featherweight division.  For more stories like this,check our sport page.  Follow Metro Sport for the latest news onFacebook,TwitterandInstagram.  ArrowMORE:Team GB star calls for Olympic rule change after being 'robbed' of Paris gold medal  ArrowMORE:'It's fraud' - Adam Peaty blasts 'cheating' Chinese swimmers at Olympics  ArrowMORE:Team GB silver medal downgraded to bronze on heartbreaking photo finish  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site